Q1. Bayes Rule (10 points)

A firm new to the renewable energy sector decided to invest in a solar project. The firm tasks your team to determine which supplier to purchase solar panels from.

  • You purchased 35% percent of panels from Mitsui, which has as a shipment defect rate of 1%.

  • You purchased 20% percent of panels from Toshiba, which ships 3% defectives.

  • You purchased the rest from Kyocera, which ships 0.5% defectives.

During construction, your electrical engineer picks a panel at random, which turns out to be defective! What is the probability that this defective panel was manufactured by Mitsui, Toshiba, and Kyocera, respectively?

  1. (5 points) You were given \(P(Defective|Mitsui)\), \(P(Defective|Toshiba)\), and \(P(Defective|Kyocera)\). What are their values?

  2. (5 points) Using Bayes rule, calculate \(P(Mitsui|Defective)\), \(P(Toshiba|Defective)\), and \(P(Kyocera|Defective)\).



Q2. AND and OR Relationships (15 points)

To figure out what went wrong, you read up more on this companys panels, and discover that it has three main components, including (A) solar cell layer, (B) tempered glass, and (C) an electrical junction box. Upon further research

  • The solar cell layer has a probability of 0.01 of failing in 1 year.

  • The glass has a probability of 0.03 of failing in 1 year.

  • The junction box has a probability of 0.05 of failing in 1 year.

  • Assume that the solar cells, tempered glass, and junction box are all independent (the failure of one component has nothing to do with other components). What is the probability that the panel survives 1 year without failing?


What is the probability that the card survives 1 year without failing?

  1. (5 points) \(P(panel \ survives) = P(Cell \ survives \ \textbf{AND} \ Glass \ survives \ \textbf{AND} \ Junction \ Box \ survives)\)

  2. (5 points) \(P(panel \ survives) = 1 - P(Cell \ fails \ \textbf{OR} \ Glass \ fails \ \textbf{OR} \ Junction \ Box \ fails)\)

  3. (5 points) Are they the same? Why or why not? (Hint: A Venn Diagram may help.)

Q3. Bayes Rule (5 points)

Your team gets hired to add rooftop solar panels to homes in a Tokyo suburb, at the height of the COVID-19 pandemic. To keep your team and the community you are working in safe, your team masks, gets vaccinated, and regularly takes COVID tests.

  • Suppose that 8.5% of local residents are infected with COVID-19.

  • Also, suppose that a COVID-19 antigen test will correctly flag as positive 94% of people who actively have COVID-19.

  • However, like all other diagnostic tests, 2% of residents who do not have COVID-19 will also test positive.

Q. (5 points) Please calculate the probability that an employee who tests positive for COVID-19 actually has COVID.

Q5. Simulation (10 points)

Tohoku University researchers wants to promote the local rooftop solar market in 400 nearby municipalities, so they hire your team to research it. They know from a firms survey that as of 2019, each of these 400 municipalities have adopted a mean of 459 units and a median of 400 units, with a standard deviation of 300.4 units. Unfortunately, there is no raw data left to work with!

  1. (5 points) Based on the type of data being analyzed, which theoretical distribution is most likely to match the distribution of rooftop solar units? Why?
  1. (5 points) Using that distribution, simulate the approximate cumulative probability of solar adoption in these 400 Tohoku municipalities, from 0 to 1000. How many municipalities do you project have adopted more than 400, 450, and 500 rooftop solar units to date, respectively?

Your team finishes building the solar farm! Huzzah! Having already sorted out any defective parts in the previous question, your solar farm is left with 300 electrical junction boxes, each with a constant failure rate $ $. Each box is expected to survive a period of 1000 days without failure, with probability 0.40.

  1. (5 points) Determine the failure rate \(\lambda\).

  2. (5 points) Whats the probability that a single box will survive 5000 days without failure?

  3. (5 points) Whats the probability that the box will fail within 5000 days, when you know that the box was functioning as of 1000 days?



Q7. Survival Functions (10)

The National Renewable Energy Lab estimates that solar panels installed between 2000 and 2015 failed a constant annual rate of just 5 panels per 10,000 panels. Your company installed 500 solar panels to form a single solar farm outside of Tokyo in 2012.

  1. (2.5 points) Whats the probability that at all 500 of these panels survived years 10 years without failing? How about just 250 of these panels? 100 panels?

  2. (5 points) Please calculate these probabilities for each year from 0 to 10 and visualize the 3 curves using ggplot2 in R. Be sure to effectively label your plot, use color, and themes.

  3. (2.5 points) Finally, please calculate the accumulative hazard rate for 1 solar panel by year 10.



Q8. System Reliability (20 points)

Prompt: Your firm is hired to install an off-grid rooftop solar system on top of a community center, to provide power for this key neighborhood resource for up to 72 hours after crisis. Local leaders want to know exactly how likely this system is to survive, considering that it involves several component parts. Your team researches each components probability of failure and make the flowchart below.

  • 75% of the year, the panels will get sufficient sunlight to function reliably.

  • Each panel has a constant rate of failure at 0.06% per year. (Note: 0.06 PERCENT, not 6%.)

  • Each storage unit has a constant rate of failure at 2% per year.

  • All other components have a constant rate of failure at 1% per year.

However, local leaders need to know the overall reliability of this system in a year!


Questions:

  1. (10 points) Calculate the overall reliability of this system in any year \(t\). (Note: Use years as your time unit of interest.)

  2. (10 points) Create an R function to estimate the overall reliability of this system in any year. Then use it to visualize the overall reliability of the system over 20 years (0 to 20) in ggplot2.

  • Hint: Write a general failure and/or reliability function (eg. f or r) first to make your code cleaner and easier.

Community Center Solar System Diagram 

# Single events

# Calculate independent reliability rate of quality sunlight
r_sun <- r(1, l_sun)
# Calculate independent reliability rate of inverter
r_inverter <- r(1, l_inverter)
# Calculate independent reliability rate of electrical panel
r_electrical <- r(1, l_electrical)


# System Reliability
r_overall <- r_sun * r_solar * r_inverter * r_electrical * r_units

# Return function result
r_overall
## [1] 0.7633736

End
